<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Slurry" class="currentChild" href="Slurry">Slurry</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A mixture of water and dissolved paper <a title="Pulp" href="Pulp">pulp</a> produced during the <a title="Stock Preparation" href="Stock_Preparation">stock preparation</a> phase of papermaking. Pulp must be dissolved in water and constantly agitated before undergoing <a title="Refining" href="Refining">refining</a> to keep paper fibers from prematurely clotting, which would have a deleterious effect on the paper produced. The <a title="Loading" href="Loading">loading</a> of non-fibrous additives is also facilitated when fibers are suspended in water. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
In ink manufacturing, <em>slurry</em> refers to the mixture of the liquid ink <a title="Vehicle" href="Vehicle">vehicle</a> and solid <a title="Pigment" href="Pigment">pigment</a> particles that undergo <a title="Mixing" href="Mixing">mixing</a> and <a title="Milling" href="Milling">milling</a>. 
</p>
